getArgumentNode(WordObj, WordObj, DependencyGraph) - Method in class ConstituencyTree
Given an argument and a predicate in a ConstituencyTree, we want to return a node which a) either dominates the argument node or is the argument node b) is directly dominated by the node which dominates both the predicate and the argument node Example: [ S [ NP [ DET The] [ N gardener] [ VP [V likes ] [ NP [ PN his ] [ N flowers ] ] ] ] ] Given that "likes" is the predicate and "gardener" is the argument, this function will first find the lowest node in the tree which dominates both the predicate and argument node (here: S: "The gardener likes his flowers").
getArgumentNodeMWE(WordObj, WordObj, List<WordObj>) - Method in class ConstituencyTree
This method is for the extraction of phrases for MWE-predicates Given an argument and an MWE-predicate in a ConstituencyTree, we want to return a node which a) either dominates the argument node or is the argument node b) is dominated by the node which dominates both the MWE-predicate and argument node c) the node must NOT dominate any token of the MWE-predicate
getArgumentString(WordObj, WordObj) - Method in class ConstituencyTree
Given an argument and a predicate in a ConstituencyTree, we want to return the String which corresponds to the phrase which a) either dominates the argument node or is the argument node b) is directly dominated by the node which dominates both the predicate and the argument node Example: [ S [ NP [ DET The] [ N gardener] [ VP [V likes ] [ NP [ PN his ] [ N flowers ] ] ] ] ] Given that "likes" is the predicate and "gardener" is the argument, this function will first find the lowest node in the tree which dominates both the predicate and argument node (here: S: "The gardener likes his flowers").
